for filename in os.listdir(folder_path):
    if filename.endswith(".jpeg"):
        # Create the new name
        new_name = filename.replace(".jpeg", ".jpg")
        
        # Join path with names and rename
        src = os.path.join(folder_path, filename)
        dst = os.path.join(folder_path, new_name)
        
        os.rename(src, dst)
        print(f'Renamed: {filename} -> {new_name}')

We resize our images with padding to all be the same size

We choose padding here for a mulitude of reasons:

  • the images are all of different sizes (pixel amounts)
  • the images do not always have the animal in the middle
  • the images are all of different aspect ratios

As such it would require a quite complicated system to cut the images into the correct shape.

We did not want to squish them as such padding remained the best choise for both machine and time efficiency.

In[25]:
def resize_with_pad(image_path, target_size=(128, 128)):
    img = tf.io.read_file(image_path)
    img = tf.image.decode_jpeg(img, channels=3)
    img = tf.image.resize_with_pad(img, target_size[0], target_size[1])
    img = img / 255.0  # Normalize
    return img

We choose the following augmentations:

  • random flip
  • random rotation
  • random zoom
  • random contract
  • random grayscale

They change the way you look at the image as well as the underlying data of the image, allowing for a variety of different compositions for the model to see the aniimals in.

For the hyperparameters we simply choose ones that changes the image, but not to drastically, they were eye measure on the example down below.

In[215]:
data_augmentation = keras.Sequential([
    RandomFlip("horizontal"),
    RandomRotation(0.1),
    RandomZoom(0.15),
    RandomContrast([0,0.3]),
    RandomGrayscale(0.1)
])

In[285]:
def eval_classification(model, test_ds, class_names=None, model_name=None):
    """Evaluate classification model and display confusion matrix."""

# Get predictions and true labels
    y_pred_probs = model.predict(test_ds, verbose=0)
    y_pred = np.argmax(y_pred_probs, axis=1)
    y_true = np.concatenate([y for x, y in test_ds], axis=0)

# Evaluate model
    test_loss, test_acc = model.evaluate(test_ds, verbose=0)

# Print results
    print(f"\n{'='*50}")
    print(f"  {model_name or 'Model'} - Classification Results")
    print(f"{'='*50}")
    print(f"  Test Loss:     {test_loss:.4f}")
    print(f"  Test Accuracy: {test_acc:.4f} ({test_acc*100:.2f}%)")
    print(f"{'='*50}\n")

    print(classification_report(y_true, y_pred, target_names=class_names))

# Create confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 8))
    disp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix=cm, display_labels=class_names)
    disp.plot(ax=ax, cmap='Blues', values_format='d')
    plt.title(f"{model_name or 'Model'} - Confusion Matrix")
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    return test_loss, test_acc

3.1) EfficientNet

First we tried it with EfficientNetV2B0 and manuall hyperparameter tuning.

  • A rescale layer is required for it to work with the pretrained network
  • the global average pooling layer is taken from the lession, it works well so we saw no need to change it (especially as this global layer greatly reduced the amount of params and thus training time)
  • the one global layer comes from bodenhofers rule of thumb (we have 3 classes so we shouldn't have more then 1.5 hidden layers) and some testing
  • 64 Neurons are enough to get a good accuracy both for training and validation, I tried a few more by hand but this one seemed to strike a good balance
  • the dropout layer is kept with a rather small rate as the model only has a few epochs, which it barely trains to the end of, especially with early stopping it a smaller rate those better from my experiance from the last EX
  • for the optimizer adam is the default choise and it is a good one
  • the loss is actually a bit tricky, as it changes depending on the function to read in the data and how it treats the lables the current lable version which uses "sparse_categorical_crossentropy" seems to work the best
In[251]:
base_model = keras.applications.EfficientNetV2B0(
    include_top=False,
    weights="imagenet",
    input_shape=(128, 128, 3),
    pooling=None
)

base_model.trainable = True
inputs = keras.Input(shape=(128, 128, 3))
inputs = layers.Rescaling(1./127.5)(inputs) # EfficientNetV2B0 takes [-1, 1] range so 1./127.5, quite hidden in documentation
x = data_augmentation(inputs, training = True)
x = base_model(x, training=True)
x = GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)
x = Dense(64, activation='relu')(x)
x = Dropout(0.05)(x)
outputs = Dense(len(OPTIONS), activation='softmax')(x)
model_effnet = Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)
model_effnet.compile(
        optimizer=keras.optimizers.Adam(),
        loss="sparse_categorical_crossentropy",
        metrics=["accuracy"]
    )
model_effnet.summary()

3.3) Our CNN

In[258]:
import keras_tuner as kt
import keras.optimizers as opt

Hypermodel

We decided to do a Hyperband Search for the best Parameters for our Custom CNN model. The input is pretty clear, its just our inputshape, then the data augmentation and afterwards we have the numbers of con Blocks which are random in between 2, 3 and 4, the filters which can be ether 16, 32, 64 and I also put the activation function in there (relu, elu and selu).

We decided to also use BatchNormalization, there is also always an option that it makes another conv layers instead of just one, also with batchNormalization.

After that we always have MaxPooling and Drop out.

Afterwards we have the Dense Units and the Dense Dropout, we only have 1 or 2 layers, as we only have 3 classes. Our Dense Units can be 16, 32, 64 or 128 and our dropout can be from min 0.0 to max 0.5. THe output layer is a Dense layer with 3 neurons and an activation of softmax.

We also have options between the optimizer and learningrate, optimizer can be adam or lion and the learning rate is in between 5e-4 and 25e-4

Our loss here is the sparse categorical crossentropy.

Our Hyperparameters aren't the biggest ones, that is because our Dataset isn't the biggest, so those parameters made the most sense for our Data. Afterwards we did Hyberband Search anyways so that we would figure out which Parameters are the best.

In[259]:
def hypermodel(hp):
    inputs = keras.layers.Input(shape=(128, 128, 3))
    
    # Add data augmentation
    x = data_augmentation(inputs)
    
    # Convolutional blocks
    num_conv_blocks = hp.Choice('num_conv_blocks', [2, 3, 4])
    filters = hp.Choice('initial_filters', [16, 32, 64])
    activation_function = hp.Choice('activation', ['relu', 'elu', 'selu'])

    
    for i in range(num_conv_blocks):
        # Conv layers in each block
        x = keras.layers.Conv2D(
            filters=filters * (2 ** i),
            kernel_size=hp.Choice(f'kernel_size_{i}', [3, 5]),
            padding='same'
        )(x)
        x = keras.layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
        x = keras.layers.Activation(hp.Choice('activation', ['relu', 'elu', 'selu']))(x)
        
        # Optional second conv in block
        if hp.Boolean(f'double_conv_{i}'):
            x = keras.layers.Conv2D(
                filters=filters * (2 ** i),
                kernel_size=3,
                padding='same'
            )(x)
            x = keras.layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
            x = keras.layers.Activation(hp.Choice('activation', ['relu', 'elu', 'selu']))(x)
        
        # Pooling
        x = keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
        x = keras.layers.Dropout(hp.Float('conv_dropout', 0.0, 0.3, sampling='linear'))(x)
    
    # Flatten
    x = keras.layers.Flatten()(x)
    
    # Dense layers
    dense_units = hp.Choice('dense_units', [16, 32, 64, 128])
    dense_dropout = hp.Float('dense_dropout', min_value=0.0, max_value=0.5, sampling='linear')
    
    for i in range(hp.Choice('num_dense_layers', [1, 2])):
        x = keras.layers.Dense(dense_units)(x)
        x = keras.layers.Activation(activation_function)(x)
        if dense_dropout > 0:
            x = keras.layers.Dropout(dense_dropout)(x)
    
    # Output layer
    outputs = keras.layers.Dense(3, activation='softmax')(x)
    model = keras.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs, name='cnn_hypermodel')
    
    # Optimizer
    optimizer_choice = hp.Choice('optimizer', ['adam', 'lion'])
    learning_rate = hp.Float('learning_rate', min_value=5e-4, max_value=25e-4, sampling='linear')
    
    if optimizer_choice == 'adam':
        optimizer = opt.Adam(learning_rate=learning_rate)
    else:
        optimizer = opt.Lion(learning_rate=learning_rate)
    
    model.compile(
        optimizer=optimizer,
        loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
        metrics=['accuracy']
    )
    
    return model

    project_name="hyperbandCNN",
)
